06359nam a22009255i 9783110601879DE-B159720230228123812.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||230228t20192019gw     fo  d z      eng d  a2019937557  a97831106018797 a10.1515/97831106018792doi  a(DE-B1597)494764  a(OCoLC)1114850159  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  agwcDE00aLC1030b.M54 2019 7aHIS0540002bisacsh  aDV 2175qSEPA2rvk0(DE-625)rvk/20084:1 aMiethe, Ingrid, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aGlobalization of an Educational Idea :bWorkers’ Faculties in Eastern Germany, Vietnam, Cuba and Mozambique /cIngrid Miethe, Tim Kaiser, Tobias Kriele, Alexandra Piepiorka. 1aMünchen ;aWien : bDe Gruyter Oldenbourg, c[2019] 4c©2019  a1 online resource (XIV, 388 p.)  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda0 aRethinking the Cold War ,x2567-5311 ;v700tFrontmatter -- tPreface -- tAcknowledgments -- tContents -- t1. Introduction -- t2. Theoretical Approaches -- t3. Methodological Considerations and Available Sources -- t4. The Starting Point: The Rabfak in Soviet Russia -- t5. The Global Dissemination of an Educational Idea -- t6. The Workers’ Faculties in the German Democratic Republic (GDR) -- t7. The Worker-Peasant Complementary Education Schools of the Democratic Republic of Vietnam -- t8. The Workers’ Faculties in Cuba -- t9. The Faculty for Former Combatants and Vanguard Workers in Mozambique -- t10. Theoretical Conclusions -- t11. Appendix -- tPersons -- tPlaces0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aIn this book, authors showcase the worldwide spread of Workers’ Faculties as an example of both cooperation between socialist countries in education, and globalization processes in the field of education. Based on extensive research carried out in Cuban, German, Mozambican, and Vietnamese archives as well as expert interviews, it combines detailed case studies of educational transfers and policy implementation with a discussion of theoretical approaches to the study of globalization in and of education.Research on Workers’ Faculties provides an especially interesting example for the study of educational transfer between socialist countries as well as for the interplay of such transfers with processes of globalisation for two reasons. On one hand, the first Workers’ Faculties were established already shortly after the October Revolution in Russia, and Workers’ Faculties continue to exist in Cuba until today. A study of these institutions therefore provides a dynamic perspective covering the whole period of the existence of the socialist camp. On the other hand, the spread of the Workers’ Faculty idea to four continents allows for an analysis that takes into account widely differing local contexts.This book offers an analysis of general trends and particularities in the history of the global spread of the Workers’ Faculty idea and its implementation in local contexts. Finally, it discusses the results with a view towards theories of globalization in the field of education as well as of specificities of processes of “socialist globalization”.  aIssued also in print.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 28. Feb 2023) 0aCommunism and education. 0aCommunist educationvCase studies. 7aHISTORY / Social History.2bisacsh1 aKaiser, Tim , eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut1 aKaiser, Tim, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aKriele, Tobias, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut1 aKriele, Tobias, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aMiethe, Ingrid, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aPiepiorka, Alexandra, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabu